sec-%typedarray%.of.summary: The TypedArray.of() method creates a new typed array with a variable number of arguments. This method is nearly the same as Array.of().

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.copywithin.summary: The copyWithin() method copies the sequence of array elements within the array to the position starting at target. The copy is taken from the index positions of the second and third arguments start and end. The end argument is optional and defaults to the length of the array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.copyWithin. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.copywithin.title: TypedArray.prototype.copyWithin()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.entries.summary: The entries() method returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the key/value pairs for each index in the array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.entries.title: TypedArray.prototype.entries()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.every.summary: The every() method tests whether all elements in the typed array pass the test implemented by the provided function. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.every(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.every.title: TypedArray.prototype.every()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.fill.summary: The fill() method fills all the elements of a typed array from a start index to an end index with a static value. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.fill(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.fill.title: TypedArray.prototype.fill()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.filter.summary: The filter() method creates a new typed array with all elements that pass the test implemented by the provided function. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.filter(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.filter.title: TypedArray.prototype.filter()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.find.summary: The find() method returns a value in the typed array, if an element satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise undefined is returned. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.find.title: TypedArray.prototype.find()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findindex.summary: The findIndex() method returns an index in the typed array, if an element in the typed array satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise -1 is returned.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findindex.title: TypedArray.prototype.findIndex()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.foreach.summary: The forEach() method executes a provided function once per array element. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.forEach(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.foreach.title: TypedArray.prototype.forEach()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.includes.summary: The includes() method determines whether a typed array includes a certain element, returning true or false as appropriate. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.includes(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.includes.title: TypedArray.prototype.includes()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.indexof.summary: The indexOf() method returns the first index at which a given element can be found in the typed array, or -1 if it is not present. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.indexOf(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.indexof.title: TypedArray.prototype.indexOf()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.join.summary: The join() method joins all elements of an array into a string. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.join(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.join.title: TypedArray.prototype.join()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.keys.summary: The keys() method returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the keys for each index in the array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.keys.title: TypedArray.prototype.keys()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.lastindexof.summary: The lastIndexOf() method returns the last index at which a given element can be found in the typed array, or -1 if it is not present. The typed array is searched backwards, starting at fromIndex. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.lastIndexOf(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.

firefox_android.notes: Starting with Firefox 47, this method will no longer return -0. For example, new Uint8Array([0]).lastIndexOf(0, -0) will now always return +0.

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.map.summary: The map() method creates a new typed array with the results of calling a provided function on every element in this typed array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.map(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.map.title: TypedArray.prototype.map()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduce.summary: The reduce() method applies a function against an accumulator and each value of the typed array (from left-to-right) has to reduce it to a single value. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.reduce(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduce.title: TypedArray.prototype.reduce()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduceRight.summary: The reduceRight() method applies a function against an accumulator and each value of the typed array (from right-to-left) has to reduce it to a single value. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.reduceRight(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduceRight.title: TypedArray.prototype.reduceRight()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reverse.summary: The reverse() method reverses a typed array in place. The first typed array element becomes the last and the last becomes the first. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.reverse(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reverse.title: TypedArray.prototype.reverse()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.set-array-off.summary: The set() method stores multiple values in the typed array, reading input values from a specified array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.set-array-off.title: TypedArray.prototype.set()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.slice.summary: The slice() method returns a shallow copy of a portion of a typed array into a new typed array object. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.slice(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.slice.title: TypedArray.prototype.slice()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.some.summary: The some() method tests whether some element in the typed array passes the test implemented by the provided function. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.some(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.some.title: TypedArray.prototype.some()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.sort.summary: The sort() method sorts the elements of a typed array numerically in place and returns the typed array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.sort(), except that sorts the values numerically instead of as strings. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.sort.title: TypedArray.prototype.sort()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.subarray.summary: The subarray() method returns a new TypedArray on the same ArrayBuffer store and with the same element types as for this TypedArray object. The begin offset is inclusive and the end offset is exclusive. TypedArray is one of the typed array types.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.subarray.title: TypedArray.prototype.subarray()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tolocalestrin.summary: The toLocaleString() method returns a string representing the elements of the typed array. The elements are converted to strings and are separated by a locale-specific string (such as a comma “,”). This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.toLocaleString() and, as the typed array elements are numbers, the same algorithm as Number.prototype.toLocaleString() applies for each element. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tolocalestrin.title: TypedArray.prototype.toLocaleString()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified array and its elements. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.toString(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tostring.title: TypedArray.prototype.toString()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.values.summary: The values() method returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the values for each index in the array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.values.title: TypedArray.prototype.values()

sec-array.prototype.concat.summary: The concat() method is used to merge two or more arrays. This method does not change the existing arrays, but instead returns a new array.
sec-array.prototype.concat.title: Array.prototype.concat()

sec-array.prototype.copywithin.summary: The copyWithin() method shallow copies part of an array to another location in the same array and returns it, without modifying its size.

sec-array.prototype.entries.summary: The entries() method returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the key/value pairs for each index in the array.

sec-array.prototype.every.summary: The every() method tests whether all elements in the array pass the test implemented by the provided function.
sec-array.prototype.every.title: Array.prototype.every()

sec-array.prototype.fill.summary: The fill() method fills all the elements of an array from a start index to an end index with a static value. The end index is not included.

sec-array.prototype.filter.summary: The filter() method creates a new array with all elements that pass the test implemented by the provided function.

sec-array.prototype.find.summary: The find() method returns the value of the first element in the array that satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise undefined is returned.
sec-array.prototype.find.title: Array.prototype.find()

sec-array.prototype.findIndex.summary: The findIndex() method returns the index of the first element in the array that satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise, it returns -1, indicating no element passed the test.

sec-array.prototype.foreach.summary: The forEach() method executes a provided function once for each array element.

sec-array.prototype.includes.summary: The includes() method determines whether an array includes a certain value among its entries, returning true or false as appropriate.

sec-array.prototype.indexof.summary: The indexOf() method returns the first index at which a given element can be found in the array, or -1 if it is not present.
sec-array.prototype.indexof.title: Array.prototype.indexOf()

sec-array.prototype.join.summary: The join() method creates and returns a new string by concatenating all of the elements in an array (or an array-like object), separated by commas or a specified separator string.
sec-array.prototype.join.title: Array.prototype.join()

sec-array.prototype.keys.summary: The keys() method returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the keys for each index in the array.
sec-array.prototype.keys.title: Array.prototype.keys()

sec-array.prototype.lastindexof.summary: The lastIndexOf() method returns the last index at which a given element can be found in the array, or -1 if it is not present. The array is searched backwards, starting at fromIndex.
sec-array.prototype.lastindexof.title: Array.prototype.lastIndexOf()

sec-array.prototype.map.summary: The map() method creates a new array with the results of calling a provided function on every element in the calling array.
sec-array.prototype.map.title: Array.prototype.map()

sec-array.prototype.pop.summary: The pop() method removes the last element from an array and returns that element. This method changes the length of the array.
sec-array.prototype.pop.title: Array.prototype.pop()

sec-array.prototype.push.summary: The push() method adds one or more elements to the end of an array and returns the new length of the array.
sec-array.prototype.push.title: Array.prototype.push()

sec-array.prototype.reduce.summary: The reduce() method executes a reducer function (that you provide) on each member of the array resulting in a single output value.
sec-array.prototype.reduce.title: Array.prototype.reduce()

sec-array.prototype.reduceright.title: Array.prototype.reduceRight()

sec-array.prototype.reverse.summary: The reverse() method reverses an array in place. The first array element becomes the last, and the last array element becomes the first.
sec-array.prototype.reverse.title: Array.prototype.reverse()

sec-array.prototype.shift.summary: The shift() method removes the first element from an array and returns that removed element. This method changes the length of the array.
sec-array.prototype.shift.title: Array.prototype.shift()

sec-array.prototype.some.summary: The some() method tests whether at least one element in the array passes the test implemented by the provided function.
sec-array.prototype.some.title: Array.prototype.some()

sec-array.prototype.sort.summary: The sort() method sorts the elements of an array in place and returns the array. The default sort order is built upon converting the elements into strings, then comparing their sequences of UTF-16 code units values.

sec-array.prototype.splice.summary: The splice() method changes the contents of an array by removing or replacing existing elements and/or adding new elements.
sec-array.prototype.splice.title: Array.prototype.splice()

sec-array.prototype.tolocalestring.summary: The toLocaleString() method returns a string representing the elements of the array. The elements are converted to Strings using their toLocaleString methods and these Strings are separated by a locale-specific String (such as a comma “,”).

sec-array.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified array and its elements.

sec-arrow-function-definitions.summary: An arrow function expression has a shorter syntax than a function expression and does not have its own this, arguments, super, or new.target. These function expressions are best suited for non-method functions, and they cannot be used as constructors.

sec-object.defineproperties.summary: The Object.defineProperties() method defines new or modifies existing properties directly on an object, returning the object.

sec-object.entries.summary: The Object.entries() method returns an array of a given object's own enumerable property [key, value] pairs, in the same order as that provided by a for...in loop (the difference being that a for-in loop enumerates properties in the prototype chain as well) . The order of the array returned by Object.entries() does not depend on how an object is defined. If there is a need for certain ordering then the array needs to be sorted first like Object.entries(obj).sort((a, b) = a[0] - b[0]);.

sec-object.freeze.summary: The Object.freeze() method freezes an object. A frozen object can no longer be changed; freezing an object prevents new properties from being added to it, existing properties from being removed, prevents changing the enumerability, configurability, or writability of existing properties, and prevents the values of existing properties from being changed. In addition, freezing an object also prevents its prototype from being changed. freeze() returns the same object that was passed in.

sec-object.getownpropertynames.summary: The Object.getOwnPropertyNames() method returns an array of all properties (including non-enumerable properties except for those which use Symbol) found directly upon a given object.

sec-object.getownpropertysymbols.summary: The Object.getOwnPropertySymbols() method returns an array of all symbol properties found directly upon a given object.
sec-object.getownpropertysymbols.title: Object.getOwnPropertySymbols()

sec-object.getprototypeof.summary: The Object.getPrototypeOf() method returns the prototype (i.e. the value of the internal [[Prototype]] property) of the specified object.

sec-object.is.summary: The Object.is() method determines whether two values are the same value.

Note that the value of this property is a reference to the function itself, not a string containing the function's name. The value is only read-only for primitive values such as 1, true and "test".
sec-object.prototype.constructor.title: Object.prototype.constructor

sec-object.prototype.hasownproperty.summary: The hasOwnProperty() method returns a boolean indicating whether the object has the specified property as its own property (as opposed to inheriting it).
sec-object.prototype.hasownproperty.title: Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty()

sec-object.prototype.isprototypeof.summary: The isPrototypeOf() method checks if an object exists in another object's prototype chain.
sec-object.prototype.isprototypeof.title: Object.prototype.isPrototypeOf()

sec-object.prototype.propertyisenumerabl.summary: The propertyIsEnumerable() method returns a Boolean indicating whether the specified property is enumerable.
sec-object.prototype.propertyisenumerabl.title: Object.prototype.propertyIsEnumerable()

sec-object.prototype.tolocalestring.summary: The toLocaleString() method returns a string representing the object. This method is meant to be overridden by derived objects for locale-specific purposes.
sec-object.prototype.tolocalestring.title: Object.prototype.toLocaleString()

sec-object.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the object.
sec-object.prototype.tostring.title: Object.prototype.toString()

sec-object.prototype.valueof.summary: The valueOf() method returns the primitive value of the specified object.
sec-object.prototype.valueof.title: Object.prototype.valueOf()

sec-object.seal.summary: The Object.seal() method seals an object, preventing new properties from being added to it and marking all existing properties as non-configurable. Values of present properties can still be changed as long as they are writable.

sec-object.setprototypeof.summary: The Object.setPrototypeOf() method sets the prototype (i.e., the internal [[Prototype]] property) of a specified object to another object or null.
sec-object.setprototypeof.title: Object.setPrototypeOf()

sec-object.values.summary: The Object.values() method returns an array of a given object's own enumerable property values, in the same order as that provided by a for...in loop (the difference being that a for-in loop enumerates properties in the prototype chain as well).

sec-promise.all.summary: The Promise.all(iterable) method returns a single Promise that resolves when all of the promises in the iterable argument have resolved or when the iterable argument contains no promises. It rejects with the reason of the first promise that rejects.
sec-promise.all.title: Promise.all()

sec-promise.prototype.summary: The Promise.prototype property represents the prototype for the Promise constructor.
sec-promise.prototype.title: Promise.prototype

sec-promise.prototype.catch.summary: The catch() method returns a Promise and deals with rejected cases only. It behaves the same as calling Promise.prototype.then(undefined, onRejected) (in fact, calling obj.catch(onRejected) internally calls obj.then(undefined, onRejected)). This means, that you have to provide onRejected function even if you want to fallback to undefined result value - for example obj.catch(() = {}).
sec-promise.prototype.catch.title: Promise.prototype.catch()

sec-promise.prototype.finally.summary: The finally() method returns a Promise. When the promise is settled, whether fulfilled or rejected, the specified callback function is executed. This provides a way for code that must be executed once the Promise has been dealt with to be run whether the promise was fulfilled successfully or rejected.
sec-promise.prototype.finally.title: Promise.prototype.finally()

sec-promise.prototype.then.summary: The then() method returns a Promise. It takes up to two arguments: callback functions for the success and failure cases of the Promise.
sec-promise.prototype.then.title: Promise.prototype.then()

sec-promise.race.summary: The Promise.race(iterable) method returns a promise that resolves or rejects as soon as one of the promises in the iterable resolves or rejects, with the value or reason from that promise.
sec-promise.race.title: Promise.race()

sec-promise.reject.summary: The Promise.reject(reason) method returns a Promise object that is rejected with the given reason.
sec-promise.reject.title: Promise.reject()

sec-promise.resolve.summary: The Promise.resolve(value) method returns a Promise object that is resolved with the given value. If the value is a promise, that promise is returned; if the value is a thenable (i.e. has a "then" method), the returned promise will "follow" that thenable, adopting its eventual state; otherwise the returned promise will be fulfilled with the value. This function flattens nested layers of promise-like objects (e.g. a promise that resolves to a promise that resolves to something) into a single layer.
sec-promise.resolve.title: Promise.resolve()

sec-properties-of-array-instances-length.summary: The length property of an object which is an instance of type Array sets or returns the number of elements in that array. The value is an unsigned, 32-bit integer that is always numerically greater than the highest index in the array.
sec-properties-of-array-instances-length.title: Array.length

sec-properties-of-regexp-instances.summary: The lastIndex is a read/write integer property of regular expression instances that specifies the index at which to start the next match.

sec-properties-of-string-instances-lengt.summary: The length property of a String object indicates the length of a string, in UTF-16 code units.

sec-reflect.apply.summary: The static Reflect.apply() method calls a target function with arguments as specified.
sec-reflect.apply.title: Reflect.apply()

sec-reflect.construct.summary: The static Reflect.construct() method acts like the new operator, but as a function. It is equivalent to calling new target(...args). It gives also the added option to specify a different prototype.
sec-reflect.construct.title: Reflect.construct()

sec-reflect.defineproperty.summary: The static Reflect.defineProperty() method is like Object.defineProperty() but returns a Boolean.
sec-reflect.defineproperty.title: Reflect.defineProperty()

sec-reflect.deleteproperty.summary: The static Reflect.deleteProperty() method allows to delete properties. It is like the delete operator as a function.
sec-reflect.deleteproperty.title: Reflect.deleteProperty()

sec-reflect.get.summary: The static Reflect.get() method works like getting a property from an object (target[propertyKey]) as a function.
sec-reflect.get.title: Reflect.get()

sec-reflect.getownpropertydescriptor.summary: The static Reflect.getOwnPropertyDescriptor() method is similar to Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(). It returns a property descriptor of the given property if it exists on the object, undefined otherwise.
sec-reflect.getownpropertydescriptor.title: Reflect.getOwnPropertyDescriptor()

sec-reflect.getprototypeof.summary: The static Reflect.getPrototypeOf() method is almost the same method as Object.getPrototypeOf(). It returns the prototype (i.e. the value of the internal [[Prototype]] property) of the specified object.
sec-reflect.getprototypeof.title: Reflect.getPrototypeOf()

sec-reflect.has.summary: The static Reflect.has() method works like the in operator as a function.
sec-reflect.has.title: Reflect.has()

sec-reflect.isextensible.summary: The static Reflect.isExtensible() method determines if an object is extensible (whether it can have new properties added to it). It is similar to Object.isExtensible(), but with some differences.
sec-reflect.isextensible.title: Reflect.isExtensible()

sec-reflect.ownkeys.summary: The static Reflect.ownKeys() method returns an array of the target object's own property keys.
sec-reflect.ownkeys.title: Reflect.ownKeys()

sec-reflect.preventextensions.summary: The static Reflect.preventExtensions() method prevents new properties from ever being added to an object (i.e. prevents future extensions to the object). It is similar to Object.preventExtensions(), but with some differences.
sec-reflect.preventextensions.title: Reflect.preventExtensions()

sec-reflect.set.summary: The static Reflect.set() method works like setting a property on an object.
sec-reflect.set.title: Reflect.set()

sec-reflect.setprototypeof.summary: The static Reflect.setPrototypeOf() method is the same method as Object.setPrototypeOf(). It sets the prototype (i.e., the internal [[Prototype]] property) of a specified object to another object or to null.
sec-reflect.setprototypeof.title: Reflect.setPrototypeOf()

sec-regexp.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the regular expression.

sec-string.prototype.includes.summary: The includes() method determines whether one string may be found within another string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.includes.title: String.prototype.includes()

sec-string.prototype.indexof.summary: The indexOf() method returns the index within the calling String object of the first occurrence of the specified value, starting the search at fromIndex. Returns -1 if the value is not found.
sec-string.prototype.indexof.title: String.prototype.indexOf()

sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.summary: The lastIndexOf() method returns the index within the calling String object of the last occurrence of the specified value, searching backwards from fromIndex. Returns -1 if the value is not found.
sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.title: String.prototype.lastIndexOf()

sec-string.prototype.localecompare.summary: The localeCompare() method returns a number indicating whether a reference string comes before or after or is the same as the given string in sort order.
sec-string.prototype.localecompare.title: String.prototype.localeCompare()

sec-string.prototype.match.summary: The match() method retrieves the matches when matching a string against a regular expression.
sec-string.prototype.match.title: String.prototype.match()

sec-string.prototype.normalize.summary: The normalize() method returns the Unicode Normalization Form of a given string (if the value isn't a string, it will be converted to one first).
sec-string.prototype.normalize.title: String.prototype.normalize()

sec-string.prototype.padend.summary: The padEnd() method pads the current string with a given string (repeated, if needed) so that the resulting string reaches a given length. The padding is applied from the end (right) of the current string.
sec-string.prototype.padend.title: String.prototype.padEnd()

sec-string.prototype.padstart.summary: The padStart() method pads the current string with another string (multiple times, if needed) until the resulting string reaches the given length.
sec-string.prototype.padstart.title: String.prototype.padStart()

sec-string.prototype.repeat.summary: The repeat() method constructs and returns a new string which contains the specified number of copies of the string on which it was called, concatenated together.
sec-string.prototype.repeat.title: String.prototype.repeat()

sec-string.prototype.replace.summary: The replace() method returns a new string with some or all matches of a pattern replaced by a replacement.
sec-string.prototype.replace.title: String.prototype.replace()

sec-string.prototype.search.summary: The search() method executes a search for a match between a regular expression and this String object.
sec-string.prototype.search.title: String.prototype.search()

sec-string.prototype.slice.summary: The slice() method extracts a section of a string and returns it as a new string, without modifying the original string.
sec-string.prototype.slice.title: String.prototype.slice()

sec-string.prototype.split.summary: The split() method splits a String object into an array of strings by separating the string into substrings, using a specified separator string to determine where to make each split.
sec-string.prototype.split.title: String.prototype.split()

sec-string.prototype.startswith.summary: The startsWith() method determines whether a string begins with the characters of a specified string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.startswith.title: String.prototype.startsWith()

sec-string.prototype.substring.summary: The substring() method returns the part of the string between the start and end indexes, or to the end of the string.
sec-string.prototype.substring.title: String.prototype.substring()

sec-string.prototype.tolocalelowercase.summary: The toLocaleLowerCase() method returns the calling string value converted to lower case, according to any locale-specific case mappings.
sec-string.prototype.tolocalelowercase.title: String.prototype.toLocaleLowerCase()

sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.summary: The toLocaleUpperCase() method returns the calling string value converted to upper case, according to any locale-specific case mappings.
sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.title: String.prototype.toLocaleUpperCase()

sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.summary: The toLowerCase() method returns the calling string value converted to lower case.
sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.title: String.prototype.toLowerCase()

sec-string.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified object.
sec-string.prototype.tostring.title: String.prototype.toString()

sec-string.prototype.touppercase.summary: The toUpperCase() method returns the calling string value converted to uppercase (the value will be converted to a string if it isn't one).
sec-string.prototype.touppercase.title: String.prototype.toUpperCase()

sec-string.prototype.trim.summary: The trim() method removes whitespace from both ends of a string. Whitespace in this context is all the whitespace characters (space, tab, no-break space, etc.) and all the line terminator characters (LF, CR, etc.).
sec-string.prototype.trim.title: String.prototype.trim()

sec-string.prototype.valueof.summary: The valueOf() method returns the primitive value of a String object.
sec-string.prototype.valueof.title: String.prototype.valueOf()

sec-string.raw.summary: The static String.raw() method is a tag function of template literals, similar to the r prefix in Python or the @ prefix in C# for string literals (yet there is a difference: see explanations in this issue). It's used to get the raw string form of template strings, that is, substitutions (e.g. ${foo}) are processed, but escapes (e.g. \n) are not.
sec-string.raw.title: String.raw()

sec-super-keyword.summary: The super keyword is used to access and call functions on an object's parent.
sec-super-keyword.title: super

sec-switch-statement.summary: The default keyword can be used in two situations in JavaScript: within a switch statement, or with an export statement.
sec-switch-statement.title: default

sec-switch-statement.summary: The default keyword can be used in two situations in JavaScript: within a switch statement, or with an export statement.
sec-switch-statement.title: default

sec-switch-statement.summary: The switch statement evaluates an expression, matching the expression's value to a case clause, and executes statements associated with that case, as well as statements in cases that follow the matching case.
sec-switch-statement.title: switch

sec-symbol-objects.summary: The Symbol() function returns a value of type symbol, has static properties that expose several members of built-in objects, has static methods that expose the global symbol registry, and resembles a built-in object class but is incomplete as a constructor because it does not support the syntax "new Symbol()".

edge.notes: Edge 12 included Symbol properties in JSON.stringify() output.

sec-symbol-objects.title: Symbol

sec-symbol.for.summary: The Symbol.for(key) method searches for existing symbols in a runtime-wide symbol registry with the given key and returns it if found. Otherwise a new symbol gets created in the global symbol registry with this key.
sec-symbol.for.title: Symbol.for()

sec-symbol.hasinstance.summary: The Symbol.hasInstance well-known symbol is used to determine if a constructor object recognizes an object as its instance. The instanceof operator's behavior can be customized by this symbol.
sec-symbol.hasinstance.title: Symbol.hasInstance

sec-symbol.isconcatspreadable.summary: The Symbol.isConcatSpreadable well-known symbol is used to configure if an object should be flattened to its array elements when using the Array.prototype.concat() method.
sec-symbol.isconcatspreadable.title: Symbol.isConcatSpreadable

sec-symbol.iterator.summary: The Symbol.iterator well-known symbol specifies the default iterator for an object. Used by for...of.
sec-symbol.iterator.title: Symbol.iterator

sec-symbol.keyfor.summary: The Symbol.keyFor(sym) method retrieves a shared symbol key from the global symbol registry for the given symbol.
sec-symbol.keyfor.title: Symbol.keyFor()

sec-symbol.match.summary: The Symbol.match well-known symbol specifies the matching of a regular expression against a string. This function is called by the String.prototype.match() method.
sec-symbol.match.title: Symbol.match

sec-symbol.prototype.summary: The Symbol.prototype property represents the prototype for the Symbol constructor.
sec-symbol.prototype.title: Symbol.prototype

sec-symbol.prototype-@@toprimitive.summary: The [@@toPrimitive]() method converts a Symbol object to a primitive value.
sec-symbol.prototype-@@toprimitive.title: Symbol.prototype[@@toPrimitive]

sec-symbol.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified Symbol object.
sec-symbol.prototype.tostring.title: Symbol.prototype.toString()

sec-symbol.prototype.valueof.summary: The valueOf() method returns the primitive value of a Symbol object.
sec-symbol.prototype.valueof.title: Symbol.prototype.valueOf()

sec-symbol.replace.summary: The Symbol.replace well-known symbol specifies the method that replaces matched substrings of a string. This function is called by the String.prototype.replace() method.
sec-symbol.replace.title: Symbol.replace

sec-symbol.search.summary: The Symbol.search well-known symbol specifies the method that returns the index within a string that matches the regular expression. This function is called by the String.prototype.search() method.
sec-symbol.search.title: Symbol.search

sec-symbol.species.summary: The well-known symbol Symbol.species specifies a function-valued property that the constructor function uses to create derived objects.
sec-symbol.species.title: Symbol.species

sec-symbol.split.summary: The Symbol.split well-known symbol specifies the method that splits a string at the indices that match a regular expression. This function is called by the String.prototype.split() method.
sec-symbol.split.title: Symbol.split

sec-symbol.toprimitive.summary: The Symbol.toPrimitive is a symbol that specifies a function valued property that is called to convert an object to a corresponding primitive value.
sec-symbol.toprimitive.title: Symbol.toPrimitive

sec-symbol.tostringtag.summary: The Symbol.toStringTag well-known symbol is a string valued property that is used in the creation of the default string description of an object. It is accessed internally by the Object.prototype.toString() method.
sec-symbol.tostringtag.title: Symbol.toStringTag

sec-symbol.unscopables.summary: The Symbol.unscopables well-known symbol is used to specify an object value of whose own and inherited property names are excluded from the with environment bindings of the associated object.
sec-symbol.unscopables.title: Symbol.unscopables

sec-template-literals.summary: Template literals are string literals allowing embedded expressions. You can use multi-line strings and string interpolation features with them. They were called "template strings" in prior editions of the ES2015 specification.
sec-template-literals.title: Template literals (Template strings)

sec-this-keyword.summary: A function's this keyword behaves a little differently in JavaScript compared to other languages. It also has some differences between strict mode and non-strict mode.
sec-this-keyword.title: this

sec-throw-statement.summary: The throw statement throws a user-defined exception. Execution of the current function will stop (the statements after throw won't be executed), and control will be passed to the first catch block in the call stack. If no catch block exists among caller functions, the program will terminate.
sec-throw-statement.title: throw

sec-try-statement.summary: The try...catch statement marks a block of statements to try, and specifies a response, should an exception be thrown.
sec-try-statement.title: try...catch

sec-typedarray-objects.summary: A TypedArray object describes an array-like view of an underlying binary data buffer. There is no global property named TypedArray, nor is there a directly visible TypedArray constructor.  Instead, there are a number of different global properties, whose values are typed array constructors for specific element types, listed below. On the following pages you will find common properties and methods that can be used with any typed array containing elements of any type.
sec-typedarray-objects.title: TypedArray

sec-typedarray.bytes_per_element.summary: The TypedArray.BYTES_PER_ELEMENT property represents the size in bytes of each element in an typed array.
sec-typedarray.bytes_per_element.title: TypedArray.BYTES_PER_ELEMENT

sec-typeof-operator.summary: The typeof operator returns a string indicating the type of the unevaluated operand.
sec-typeof-operator.title: typeof

sec-undefined.summary: The global undefined property represents the primitive value undefined. It is one of JavaScript's primitive types.
sec-undefined.title: undefined

sec-value-properties-of-the-global-objec.summary: The global Infinity property is a numeric value representing infinity.
sec-value-properties-of-the-global-objec.title: Infinity

sec-value-properties-of-the-global-objec.summary: The global NaN property is a value representing Not-A-Number.
sec-value-properties-of-the-global-objec.title: NaN

sec-variable-statement.summary: The var statement declares a variable, optionally initializing it to a value.
sec-variable-statement.title: var

sec-void-operator.summary: The void operator evaluates the given expression and then returns undefined.
sec-void-operator.title: void operator

sec-weakmap-objects.summary: The WeakMap object is a collection of key/value pairs in which the keys are weakly referenced.  The keys must be objects and the values can be arbitrary values.
sec-weakmap-objects.title: WeakMap

sec-weakmap.prototype.summary: The WeakMap.prototype property represents the prototype for the WeakMap constructor.
sec-weakmap.prototype.title: WeakMap.prototype

sec-weakmap.prototype.delete.summary: The delete() method removes the specified element from a WeakMap object.

firefox.notes: Prior to Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. This has been fixed in version 38 and later to return false as per the ES2015 standard.

firefox_android.notes: Prior to Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. This has been fixed in version 38 and later to return false as per the ES2015 standard.

sec-weakmap.prototype.delete.title: WeakMap.prototype.delete()

sec-weakmap.prototype.get.summary: The get() method returns a specified element from a WeakMap object.

firefox.notes: Prior to Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. However, the ES2015 specification specifies to return undefined instead. Furthermore, WeakMap.prototype.get accepted an optional second argument as a fallback value, which is not part of the standard. Both non-standard behaviors are removed in version 38 and higher.

firefox_android.notes: Prior to Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. However, the ES2015 specification specifies to return undefined instead. Furthermore, WeakMap.prototype.get accepted an optional second argument as a fallback value, which is not part of the standard. Both non-standard behaviors are removed in version 38 and higher.

sec-weakmap.prototype.get.title: WeakMap.prototype.get()

sec-weakmap.prototype.has.summary: The has() method returns a boolean indicating whether an element with the specified key exists in the WeakMap object or not.

firefox.notes: Prior to Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. This has been fixed in version 38 and later to return false as per the ES2015 standard.

firefox_android.notes: Prior to Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. This has been fixed in version 38 and later to return false as per the ES2015 standard.

sec-weakmap.prototype.has.title: WeakMap.prototype.has()

sec-weakmap.prototype.set.summary: The set() method adds a new element with a specified key and value to a WeakMap object.

firefox.notes: Prior to Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. This has been fixed in version 38 and later to return false as per the ES2015 standard.

firefox_android.notes: Prior to Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. This has been fixed in version 38 and later to return false as per the ES2015 standard.

sec-weakmap.prototype.set.title: WeakMap.prototype.set()

sec-weakset-objects.summary: The WeakSet object lets you store weakly held objects in a collection.
sec-weakset-objects.title: WeakSet

sec-weakset.prototype.summary: The WeakSet.prototype property represents the prototype for the WeakSet constructor.
sec-weakset.prototype.title: WeakSet.prototype

sec-weakset.prototype.add.summary: The add() method appends a new object to the end of a WeakSet object.
sec-weakset.prototype.add.title: WeakSet.prototype.add()

sec-weakset.prototype.delete.summary: The delete() method removes the specified element from a WeakSet object.
sec-weakset.prototype.delete.title: WeakSet.prototype.delete()

sec-weakset.prototype.has.summary: The has() method returns a boolean indicating whether an object exists in a WeakSet or not.
sec-weakset.prototype.has.title: WeakSet.prototype.has()

sec-while-statement.summary: The while statement creates a loop that executes a specified statement as long as the test condition evaluates to true. The condition is evaluated before executing the statement.
sec-while-statement.title: while

table-49.summary: The Float32Array typed array represents an array of 32-bit floating point numbers (corresponding to the C float data type) in the platform byte order. If control over byte order is needed, use DataView instead. The contents are initialized to 0. Once established, you can reference elements in the array using the object's methods, or using standard array index syntax (that is, using bracket notation).
table-49.title: Float32Array

table-49.summary: The Float64Array typed array represents an array of 64-bit floating point numbers (corresponding to the C double data type) in the platform byte order. If control over byte order is needed, use DataView instead. The contents are initialized to 0. Once established, you can reference elements in the array using the object's methods, or using standard array index syntax (that is, using bracket notation).
table-49.title: Float64Array

table-49.title: Int16Array

The contents are initialized to 0. Once established, you can reference elements in the array using the object's methods, or using standard array index syntax (that is, using bracket notation).
table-49.title: Int32Array

table-49.title: Int8Array

The contents are initialized to 0. Once established, you can reference elements in the array using the object's methods, or using standard array index syntax (that is, using bracket notation).
table-49.title: Uint16Array

The contents are initialized to 0. Once established, you can reference elements in the array using the object's methods, or using standard array index syntax (that is, using bracket notation).

table-49.summary: The Uint8ClampedArray typed array represents an array of 8-bit unsigned integers clamped to 0-255; if you specified a value that is out of the range of [0,255], 0 or 255 will be set instead; if you specify a non-integer, the nearest integer will be set. The contents are initialized to 0. Once established, you can reference elements in the array using the object's methods, or using standard array index syntax (that is, using bracket notation).
